{"builtWith":"0.15.15","comments":[{"LineComment":" ━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━"},{"LineComment":"                                         // hydrogen // submodular // function"},{"LineComment":" ━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━"},{"LineComment":" | Submodular Function Types with Phantom Monotonicity"},{"LineComment":" |"},{"LineComment":" | A function f: 2^V → ℝ is submodular if for all A ⊆ B ⊆ V and x ∉ B:"},{"LineComment":" |   f(A ∪ {x}) - f(A) ≥ f(B ∪ {x}) - f(B)"},{"LineComment":" |"},{"LineComment":" | This is the \"diminishing returns\" property: adding an element to a smaller"},{"LineComment":" | set provides at least as much gain as adding it to a larger set."},{"LineComment":" |"},{"LineComment":" | ## Monotonicity as Phantom Type"},{"LineComment":" |"},{"LineComment":" | We use phantom types `Monotone` and `NonMonotone` to track function properties"},{"LineComment":" | at compile time. This ensures we cannot accidentally use a non-monotone function"},{"LineComment":" | where a monotone one is required for correctness guarantees."},{"LineComment":" |"},{"LineComment":" | - Monotone + Matroid: Greedy achieves (1 - 1/e) ≈ 0.632 approximation"},{"LineComment":" | - Non-monotone: Best known is 1/2 approximation"},{"LineComment":" |"},{"LineComment":" | ## Curvature as Value"},{"LineComment":" |"},{"LineComment":" | Curvature κ ∈ [0,1] is value-level because it's typically computed from"},{"LineComment":" | the function's parameters, not statically known. κ = 0 means modular (linear),"},{"LineComment":" | κ = 1 means maximally curved (steepest diminishing returns)."}],"decls":[{"annotation":{"meta":null,"sourceSpan":{"end":[0,0],"start":[0,0]}},"bindType":"NonRec","expression":{"abstraction":{"annotation":{"meta":{"metaType":"IsForeign"},"sourceSpan":{"end":[119,40],"start":[119,38]}},"type":"Var","value":{"identifier":"append","moduleName":["Data","Semigroup"]}},"an